  "prompt": "Why do jain sadhus do not wear clothes?",
  "response": "Jain sadhus, particularly those belonging to the Digambara sect of Jainism, do not wear clothes as part of their spiritual practice and commitment to a life of austerity and non-attachment. This practice is rooted in several key principles of Jainism:\n\n1. **Non-Attachment**: Clothing is considered a form of attachment to material possessions. By renouncing clothes, sadhus aim to detach themselves from all worldly possessions and desires, focusing solely on spiritual growth.\n\n2. **Austerity**: Jain sadhus strive to live a life of extreme austerity. Not wearing clothes is seen as an ultimate form of self-denial and discipline, reflecting their dedication to a simple and ascetic lifestyle.\n\n3. **Non-Violence (Ahimsa)**: Jainism emphasizes non-violence towards all living beings. Some sadhus believe that wearing clothes might inadvertently harm small insects or microorganisms, so they choose to go without to minimize any potential harm.\n\n4. **Purity**: The Digambara sect believes that true purity and liberation can only be achieved by renouncing all material possessions, including clothing. The term \"Digambara\" itself means \"sky-clad,\" signifying their practice of wearing the sky as their garment.\n\n5. **Spiritual Freedom**: By rejecting clothing, sadhus symbolize their freedom from societal norms and conventions, focusing instead on their spiritual journey towards enlightenment and liberation (moksha).\n\nIt's important to note that not all Jain sadhus practice nudity; those from the Svetambara sect, for example, do wear white clothes as a symbol of purity. The choice to wear or not wear clothes varies based on the specific traditions and beliefs within different Jain sects.",
